      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Biliary atresia </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Biliary atresia&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">is a condition in which the normal <strong>extrahepatic biliary system is disrupted.</strong> Progressive damage of <strong>extrahepatic and intrahepatic bile ducts</strong> secondary to inflammation may occur, leading to <strong>fibrosis, biliary cirrhosis</strong>, and eventual liver failure. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Biliary atresia is characterized by <strong>luminal obstruction of the extrahepatic bile</strong> duct with a <strong>fibrous ductal remnant </strong>representing the <strong>obliterated duct in the porta hepatis</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The primary therapy is surgical.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>&ldquo;Biliary atresia </strong>is the <strong>most common indication for liver transplantation </strong>in <strong>children</strong>, followed by <strong>metabolic and inborn disorders</strong>, <strong>autoimmune </strong>and <strong>familial cholestatic disorders</strong>, and acute hepatic necrosis.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>A. Weil&rsquo;s disease:</strong> This condition, caused by <strong>Leptospira bacteria</strong>, can <strong>lead to severe liver damage </strong>but is not the leading cause of liver transplantation in children.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>B. Fulminant hepatic failure:</strong> While this <strong>acute liver failure </strong>could necessitate <strong>urgent liver transplantation</strong>, it is not as common as biliary atresia in pediatric patients requiring this intervention.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>D. Wilson&#39;s disease:</strong> A <strong>genetic disorder </strong>that causes <strong>copper accumulation in organs</strong>, including the <strong>liver</strong>. Although it can lead to liver failure, biliary atresia is more frequently the cause of liver transplantation in the pediatric population.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Biliary atresia </strong>is the most prevalent indication for <strong>liver transplantation in the pediatric demographic</strong>, underscoring the significance of early detection and intervention to avert the progression to irreversible liver damage.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:</span></span></u></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition, Chapter-383. Page No 8277. </strong></span></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong> </strong></span></span></span></p>",
