      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>D) A3 B1 C4 D2.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A. Delayed passage of Meconium&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">is typically associated with <strong>Hirschsprung&#39;s disease (3)</strong>, a condition characterized by the <strong>absence of ganglion cells in the distal colon</strong>, leading to functional obstruction and delayed meconium passage.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">B. Red currant Jelly Stools&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">are a hallmark sign of <strong>Intussusception (1)</strong>, where <strong>part of the intestine telescopes into an adjacent segment</strong>, causing ischemia and bleeding into the lumen, which results in the &quot;red currant jelly&quot; appearance of stools.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">C. Perianal rash with acidic stools&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">is often seen in cases of <strong>Lactose intolerance (4)</strong>, where the <strong>unabsorbed lactose in the colon is fermented</strong>, producing lactic acid and other fatty acids, leading to acidic stools and potential skin irritation around the anus.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">D. Metabolic alkalosis with paradoxical aciduria&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">is a classic finding in <strong>Infantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (2)</strong>, where prolonged vomiting leads to loss of hydrochloric acid from the stomach. The body compensates by increasing urinary excretion of hydrogen ions and potassium, resulting in paradoxical aciduria despite systemic alkalosis.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational objective: </span></span></u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/27/picture19.jpg\" style=\"height:173px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></u></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref: Nelson 21<sup>st</sup> Edition</span></strong></span></span></p>",
